args:
Chronos's scheme leaves Vania in critical
condition, so at Grimnir's suggestion, the prince
and his friends decide to seek an audience with
the Rose Queen to enlist her aid.
I see your Tuner's title is not entirely\nin vain.
Heh... You are but a leaf twisting in the\nwind of my mighty storm, unable to fight\nor flee before me.
If you would fain use your dying gasps\nto speak, I'll deign to hear your words.
I have no interest in playing along with\nyour theatrics. I shall withdraw, for now.
Regrettable that I should not deal the coup\nde grace myself, but the vampire princess\nbreathes her last. My task here is done.
Farewell, Tuner. And to you, vessel.\nThe flood of time has already begun.\nI suggest you waste no effort resisting.
...Huh? Wait, what? Did he get away?\nI just said he couldn't do that like thirty\nseconds ago. Now I look like a total...
Er, hail, Prince! It seems our fates\nat long last cross. May the heavens\nthemselves bless this meeting.
Yeah, can all that garbage WAIT?!
Hey, ＂garbage＂ is awfully harsh...\nIt takes me a really long time to think\nthese lines up!
NOT. NOW. {player_name}, Vania\nlooks like she's really hurting!
Apologies, Grimnir. We'll have to speak\nlater. Let's get Vania back to the Halidom\nfor now.
How is she? Any sign of improvement?
I'm afraid I cannot say without even\nknowing what's causing her condition.
Blood. Chronos spoke true when he said\nthe prince's blood holds tremendous\npower.
Then I am the cause? I poisoned her?
Most likely. I'll admit even I'm not an\nexpert, though. I don't know how to treat\nwhat's happening to her.
I see... Not even you know.
Hey, {player_name}...\nWho is this...sorry, Grimnir, was it?\nYou fellas know each other?
Ah! In my haste, I fear I introduced myself\nonly to the prince. Hark, for I shall make\nknown my identity to one and all!
I am a god of war, emissary from the\nsteward of fate whose domain is all that\nlies 'tween cause and consequence.
Winds scour the field of battle at the\ncommand of this austere Tuner.\nI am the mad cyclone—GRIIIIIMNIIIIIR!
Um, did I... Did you guys not hear that?\nSorry, we'll do it over. I AM A GOD OF—
NO! No no... Yeah, it's not that we didn't\nhear you. It's just, uh... Well? It's that we\ngot no idea what you're talkin' about.
But...I said I was a god of war?\nCome as emissary to the keeper of fate?
...Right. Let's begin there, then. Just who\nis this ＂keeper of fate＂ you mention?
You could say they watch over the flow of\ntime.
Though it happens rarely, beings like\nChronos who can travel through time and\nacross worlds will sometimes appear.
When they start warping time for selfish\npurposes or stir up other trouble, the\nkeeper sends us to deal with it.
Warping time itself... Is Vania so\nimportant a being as to merit that?
To them, yes. Chronos came back to this\ntime from the distant future.
Their world and ours are alike, yet apart—\ntheir timeline was ravaged by the Other.
There, the princess has awakened as the\nvampire queen and is fighting back against\nthat evil.
Ravaged by the Other?! That is to be the\nfuture of our world?
That is one possibility among many.\nBut there is no immutable link between\nyour world and his.
I've heard the otherworld is a place of\ninfinite possibility—the result of branching\npaths that did not come to pass in ours.
So you're sayin' the past and the future are\ntwo different worlds?
Okay, for argument's sake, say Chronos\nkills me here. What happens to the me\nin HIS world?
I couldn't say for certain...but I do not\nbelieve that the other Ranzal would\nsuddenly disappear should you die here.
The worlds are different, but they resonate.\nThey share a kind of gravity, with one\ninfluencing the other.
If the vampire princess falls in this world,\nthe queen of the night in his world will\nfeel its effects.
That was Chronos's purpose in crossing\ntime to come here: to eliminate her before\nshe fully awakens to her powers.
As a trueblood vampire, she is nearly\nimmortal. Even for him, ending her life\nis no simple feat.
So he used my blood to that end...
Yes. Taking in exceptionally potent blood\nis an act that comes with considerable\nrisk for a vampire.
She is still too young in this timeline to\nwithstand its effects.
Rgh... I should never have allowed\nChronos to deceive me.
So is there any way we can help her now?
Seek the forbidden wood, sealed in briar.\nThe thorny monarch who there dwells may\nhave some answers.
The Rose Queen, guardian of the forest\ndeep.
The vampires' resting place lies within that\nforbidden wood. She stands vigil over their\nsleep, in keeping with an ancient accord.
Few know more of vampires than she.\nPerhaps she is aware of some way to save\nthe princess from her plight.
And do you know where this wood lies?
Then you would travel there? It likely has\nreason to deserve the name ＂forbidden.＂\nI cannot say what dangers there await.
I bear responsibility for Vania's condition.\nI want to do all that I'm able to help her.
Then so be it. I shall respect your resolve,\nmy sworn compatriot.
Sworn...? Did I miss the part where I\nswore to something?
The oath we share is above base words!\nFor it is by fate itself that our paths cross.\nNow, come! I shall be your guiding wind!
Right. We'll make Vania better,\nwhatever it takes!
You're just gonna leave me hanging?!\nCome ON! That was totally—Prince? Can\nI at least get a high five or something?!
